Preheat your oven to 200°C. Heat a #medium saucepan{} over medium-high heat (no oil). Once hot, add the @sesame seeds{15} and cook, stirring, until golden brown, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> Watch them like a hawk as they can burn easily.

Pop the toasted sesame seeds into a #small bowl{} and set aside. Don't wash the pan up! Halve, peel and chop the @red onion{1} into small pieces. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a garlic press).

Return the #saucepan{} to medium high heat with a drizzle of @olive oil{}. Once hot, add the onion and cook, stirring frequently, until soft, ~{4-5%minutes}. Add the garlic and cook, stirring, for ~{1%minute} more.

Pour the @water{240} for the bulgur wheat into the saucepan along with the @vegetable stock powder{1} and bring to the boil. Stir in the @bulgur wheat{120}, bring back up to the boil and simmer for ~{1%minute}. Pop a lid on the pan and remove from the heat. Leave to the side for ~{12-15%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, halve the @halloumi{250} lengthways so you have 2 'steaks' from each block. Cut each of these steaks in half so you have 2 triangles per person.

Line a #baking tray{} with #baking paper{} and drizzle with @olive oil{}. Arrange the halloumi triangles on the baking tray. Drizzle the @honey{15} over the triangles, spreading it with the back of a #spoon{} so the tops are evenly coated.

Sprinkle over the toasted sesame seeds, lightly pressing them so that they stick to the halloumi. Pop into the oven until the halloumi is golden brown, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Zest and halve the @lemon{1/2}. Quarter the @baby plum tomatoes{125}. Trim the @spring onion{1} then slice thinly.

Pick the @mint{1} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks). Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Once the bulgur wheat is cooked, fluff it up with a #fork{}, add the lemon zest, juice and @olive oil{} and fold it through. Add the tomatoes, spring onion, mint and parsley and stir this through. Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Divide the tabbouleh between plates and top with the sesame-crusted halloumi. Enjoy!